## From Remediation to Formal Commitment

Day 62 completed the pre-authorization remediation work — all three Moderate findings resolved before the authorization package was submitted, two Low findings resolved as documentation updates, and four Low findings appropriately deferred. The Security Assessment Report now reflects post-remediation status. Task A-6 produces the formal POA&M that will accompany the authorization package: a structured, evidence-backed commitment from the system owner to the AO about how and when the remaining open items will be addressed.

The POA&M is not new to this project — we have been maintaining a running POA&M since Day 50, when the first gaps surfaced during SSP writing. What Task A-6 requires is a formal consolidation and update: incorporating the assessment findings that were deferred to the POA&M, updating existing items based on the assessor's status review, adding the CP-2 scope revision the assessor recommended, and producing a single coherent document that the AO can use as an input to the authorization decision.

One thing I want to be direct about before getting into the entries: the original content for today described POA&M items for a default admin account with a weak password and unencrypted RDS snapshots. Those specific findings were corrected before Day 59's assessment even began — during Task I-1 implementation verification in Days 54 and 55. The POA&M I am producing today reflects the actual open items from this project's full arc, not hypothetical findings that were already resolved.

