## What Actually Clicked for Me

The insight that clarified POA&M writing today is the concept of the compensating control — and why it is not optional documentation.

When the AO reviews a POA&M, they are not just asking "what gaps exist?" They are asking "what is the risk exposure during the period while this gap remains open?" The compensating control section of each POA&M entry answers that question. It tells the AO: we have identified this gap, we have a plan to close it, and in the meantime, here is what is in place to reduce the risk while the remediation is in progress.

Without compensating controls documentation, the AO is being asked to authorize a system with acknowledged gaps and no information about what is protecting against those gaps in the interim. That is a much harder authorization decision. With compensating controls documented, the AO can evaluate whether the residual risk during the remediation period is acceptable given the specific protections in place.

Writing the compensating control descriptions forced me to think carefully about each gap — not just "what will we fix?" but "what is actually protecting the system right now, while this gap exists?" That is a more rigorous and more honest risk picture than a POA&M that is purely a remediation schedule.

