### POA&M Item 001: Clinical Downtime Procedures — CP-2

**Control Reference:** CP-2 (Contingency Plan), CP-3 (Contingency Training)

**Weakness Summary:** Clinical downtime procedures for operating OpenMRS during an EHR outage are not complete, reviewed, or tested. A draft document exists but covers only two of approximately five functional areas (patient registration and basic encounter documentation). Medication management, laboratory result handling, and complex care plan continuity during downtime are not addressed. The draft has not been reviewed by clinical leadership.

**Source:** Identified during Day 51 SSP administrative control implementation; confirmed and scope-updated by assessor in SAR (POA&M-CP2-01 scope description requires revision).

**Risk Level:** Moderate (for a High-impact system where the EHR is used for real-time clinical decision support and no tested paper-based backup procedure exists, the availability of clinical downtime procedures is a patient safety issue, not just a compliance issue).

**Point of Contact:** Health IT Manager (primary), ISSO (secondary)

**Planned Milestones:**

| Milestone | Description | Target Date | Status |
|---|---|---|---|
| 1 | Clinical leadership review of existing draft; identify all functional areas requiring procedures | [date + 15 days] | Open |
| 2 | Complete draft for all five functional areas (registration, encounter documentation, medication management, lab result handling, care plan continuity) | [date + 45 days] | Open |
| 3 | Clinical leadership formal review and approval | [date + 60 days] | Open |
| 4 | Clinical staff tabletop walkthrough of complete procedures | [date + 75 days] | Open |
| 5 | Procedures formally incorporated into contingency plan; CP-2 POA&M item closed | [date + 90 days] | Open |

**Compensating Control:** Technical recovery procedures are fully implemented and tested (4-hour RTO demonstrated in quarterly restoration test). The IT Administrator can restore the OpenMRS system from backup within the documented RTO. The gap is in clinical operational procedures during the downtime period — the technical recovery capability is in place, but clinical staff preparedness for the interval between outage and recovery is not fully addressed.

**AO Notes:** This is the highest-priority open POA&M item for a High-impact clinical system. The assessor noted that the scope of the existing draft is more limited than the prior POA&M entry implied. The 90-day target represents an aggressive but achievable timeline given the clinical leadership engagement required.

