### POA&M Item 005: Patient-Record-Level CloudWatch Anomaly Queries — AU-6

**Control Reference:** AU-6 (Audit Log Review, Analysis, and Reporting), AU-6(1) (Automated Process Integration)

**Weakness Summary:** CloudWatch log metric filters and alarms are configured for authentication anomalies (failed login spikes) and application errors. However, patient-record-level anomaly detection — queries that would alert on unusual access patterns such as a single user accessing an atypically large number of patient records in a short window — has not been fully specified or implemented. This type of insider threat detection is particularly relevant for a healthcare EHR.

**Source:** Identified during Day 52 continuous monitoring strategy work; confirmed accurate by assessor.

**Risk Level:** Low (standard authentication and application monitoring is in place; the gap is a more sophisticated insider threat detection capability layer).

**Point of Contact:** ISSO (query design), IT Administrator (CloudWatch implementation)

**Planned Milestones:**

| Milestone | Description | Target Date | Status |
|---|---|---|---|
| 1 | Define anomaly detection criteria: what constitutes an unusual patient record access pattern for MyClinic's clinical environment (e.g., >50 distinct patient records accessed by a single user in a 4-hour window) | [date + 30 days] | Open |
| 2 | Implement CloudWatch Logs Insights queries and metric filters for the defined criteria | [date + 45 days] | Open |
| 3 | Configure SNS alarms for threshold breaches; test with synthetic access pattern | [date + 60 days] | Open |
| 4 | POA&M item closed; anomaly detection criteria documented in continuous monitoring strategy | [date + 75 days] | Open |

**Compensating Control:** All patient record accesses are logged in the OpenMRS application audit log with user identifier, patient MRN, action type, and timestamp. Manual review of access patterns is possible on demand for specific investigation needs. ISSO's weekly CloudTrail review would surface any large-scale anomalous access events visible at the infrastructure level.

