## A Real-World Example That Made This Click

While writing the compensating control documentation for POA&M Item 001 (clinical downtime procedures) today, I found myself thinking carefully about how to articulate the residual risk during the remediation period — and the right real-world example came from the **2017 WannaCry ransomware attack on the UK National Health Service**.

The WannaCry attack affected approximately a third of NHS England trusts, causing widespread EHR outages. In trusts where clinical downtime procedures were documented and regularly drilled, clinical staff reverted to paper-based workflows within minutes — patients continued to be seen, medications were managed from physical records, and the operational impact, while significant, was manageable. In trusts without tested downtime procedures, clinical staff were uncertain how to proceed without the EHR — some appointments were cancelled, some clinical decisions were delayed, and the disruption was substantially greater.

The NHS WannaCry experience illustrates exactly why POA&M Item 001 carries a Moderate risk rating rather than Low, even though the technical recovery capability is in place. Technical recovery addresses the time to restore the EHR. Clinical downtime procedures address what happens to patients during that recovery window. For a system categorized as High for availability specifically because it is used for real-time clinical decision support, the 90-minute to 4-hour window between an outage and recovery is clinically significant — and untrained clinical staff in that window is a patient safety gap, not just a compliance gap.

That is why Item 001 is the highest-priority open POA&M item and why the 90-day target is described as aggressive but important, not flexible.

