## What I Am Still Thinking About

One structural question from today's POA&M work: what is the right review cadence for the AO to stay informed about POA&M status during the authorization period?

NIST SP 800-137 (Continuous Monitoring) provides guidance that POA&M items should be reviewed regularly — monthly or quarterly depending on severity — and that the AO should be notified when items are closed, when target dates are revised, or when new items are added. For MyClinic, a quarterly POA&M status report to the AO feels right — short enough to maintain accountability, infrequent enough not to create administrative burden that overshadows the actual remediation work.

The quarterly POA&M status report should include: items closed since the last report (with evidence references), items revised (with rationale for any target date changes), and any new items added through the continuous monitoring process. It should be a one-page summary with the full POA&M attached as a reference — not a lengthy narrative that buries the key status information in prose.

I want to add a standing quarterly POA&M review to the continuous monitoring calendar — the same calendar that tracks quarterly restoration tests, access reviews, and vulnerability scans. Making POA&M reporting a calendar-driven process rather than a discretionary activity is the same discipline that fixed the AT-2 quarterly training review gap. Process regularity is what closes the gap between policy and practice.

